{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15101"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15101"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.1,0.25,0.15,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67285"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7789"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52737"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3836"},{"type":"tags","id":"3874"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22531"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67285"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive lower back pain and unexplained weight loss of 8 kg. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. Digital rectal examination reveals an enlarged, hard, irregular prostate gland. Blood tests show prostate specific antigen (PSA) 245 \u00b5g/L (0-4). A bone scan shows multiple areas of increased uptake throughout the axial skeleton. A prostate biopsy is performed, showing sheets of poorly differentiated cells with no gland formation, marked nuclear pleomorphism, and frequent mitoses throughout all cores.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following Gleason scores is most consistent with these histological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gleason 6 (3+3)","Gleason 7 (3+4)","Gleason 8 (4+4)","Gleason 9 (4+5)","Gleason 10 (5+5)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with metastatic prostate cancer, as evidenced by the markedly elevated PSA, bone metastases, and concerning clinical features. The histological description indicates a highly aggressive, poorly differentiated tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Gleason grade is\u00a0primarily based on the architecture of the malignant cells within the tumour and the degree of differentiation of those cells. The pattern scale is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 1 - Small, uniform glands (well differentiated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 2 - More stroma between glands (moderately differentiated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 3 - Infiltration of cells from marginal glands (moderately differentiated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 4 - Irregular masses of neoplastic cells with few glands (poorly differentiated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 5 - Few or no glands and sheets of cells (poorly differentiated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Gleason Score is a sum of two numbers.\u00a0The two numbers are the Gleason grade of the predominant pattern and the grade of the next most common pattern. If the tumour has only one Gleason grade, this figure is then is doubled. The score is presented as the sum of two numbers, eg 5-4=9. Here, the predominant architectural pattern is pattern 5 and the secondary pattern is 4. If the predominant pattern was 4, the secondary grade would be pattern 5, and the Gleason Score would be 9.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGleason 6 (3+3)\u003C/strong\u003E represents well-differentiated cancer with discrete glandular units and would not typically present with such aggressive clinical features or metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGleason 7 (3+4)\u003C/strong\u003E shows predominantly well-formed glands with some poorly formed/fused glands. This pattern is more aggressive than Gleason 6 but would not typically present with such extensive metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGleason 8 (4+4)\u003C/strong\u003E shows poorly formed/fused glands throughout but still maintains some glandular features, unlike the complete loss of architecture described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGleason 9 (4+5)\u003C/strong\u003E is highly aggressive but would still show some attempt at gland formation in at least part of the specimen, which is not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGleason 10 (5+5)\u003C/strong\u003E represents the most aggressive pattern of prostate cancer, characterised by sheets of poorly differentiated cells with complete loss of glandular architecture, marked nuclear pleomorphism, and frequent mitoses. This pattern correlates with the aggressive clinical presentation, including metastatic disease at diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Gleason grading system is based on architectural patterns rather than cytological features. Pattern 5 is characterised by sheets of tumour cells with complete loss of glandular architecture, which matches the histological description provided. When combined with the aggressive clinical presentation, extensive metastases, and markedly elevated PSA, Gleason 10 (5+5) is most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A Gleason score of 10 (5+5) represents the most aggressive form of prostate cancer with poor differentiation and worse prognosis.","High PSA levels, bone pain, and weight loss suggest metastatic prostate cancer at presentation.","Digital rectal examination findings of a hard, irregular prostate are characteristic of prostate cancer."],"references":["Epstein JI. An update of the Gleason grading system. J Urol. 2010 Feb;183(2):433-40. doi: 10.1016/j.juro.2009.10.046. Epub 2009 Dec 14. PMID: 20006878.","Munjal A, Leslie SW. Gleason Score. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553178/","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52737"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15101"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52737"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T18:00:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T19:54:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7789"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRe